3. But `p ≡ 3 mod 4` implies `(p-1)/2` is odd, so `(-1)^((p-1)/2) ≡ -1 mod p`.
4. Therefore, `1 ≡ -1 mod p`, so `p` divides `2`, hence `p = 2`.
5. But `p ≡ 3 mod 4` implies `p ≠ 2`, a contradiction.

Thus, no such `a` exists unless `p = 2`, but `p ≡ 3 mod 4` rules that out. 

